summary.seg: The manuscript is a copy, written by the Dutch philologist and historian Theodore Rycke (1640-1690; latinized Theodorus Ryckius), of the alphabetical index of authors and works of the Greek manuscripts of the Vatican Library. The index is based on the "Grande Inventario" of the Vaticani Graeci 1-1486 by Leone Allacci (ca. 1586-1669), drawn up between 1614 and 1630 (tom. 1-2 now Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Vatt. gr. 2668-2669 olim Sala Cons. MSS 321-322 rosso; tom. 3 Bibliotheca Apostolica Vaticana, Vat. gr. 2664 olim Sala Cons. MSS 323 rosso). Between 1667 and 1669, Lorenzo Porzio (1604-1676; scriptor Graecus in the Vatican Library from 1654 to 1676), wrote the alphabetical index in three volumes, now collected in Vat. gr. 2665 (olim Sala Cons. MSS 42 (1-3) rosso: tom. 1, tom. 2, tom. 3). Rycke's copy appears in an abridged form and the classmarks and folios of the manuscripts have not been noted consistently.

support.material: ff. 1r-115v Western paper, folded in quarto. Watermark: Cock over triple mount in a circle ( 40 40 ) in the middle of the folio.

supportDesc.foliation: The leaves are foliated in pencil in Arabic numerals in the upper right-hand corner, recto.
supportDesc.collation: The quires have been sewn very tightly and the structure is difficult to determine confidently. Catchwords present on about half of the leaves, with no relation to quires; also present on rectos on ff. 99r-104r.
supportDesc.condition: The corners of the textblock are worn and rounded. Tears along the foredges, brittle at the very edges.

layoutDesc.layout:
ff. 1r-111r: written space 230 175
Two columns, 36 to 41 lines per column.

handNote.p: Manuscript written by Theodore Rycke (1640-1690) Ryckius, Theodorus, 1640-1690 in 1669.

additions.p: A note in pencil on f. [i] recto: Rycke was in Rome in 1669. Title in black ink on f. 1.

binding.p: 17th century, couched-laminate board binding covered in quarter mid-brown calfskin with marbled paper. Abridged title is tooled in gold on the spine. Left inner joint is partially split, the right inner joint is fully split.

history.origin: The manuscript was copied in Rome by Theodore de Rycke (1640-1690), a Dutch philologist, in 1669, as stated on the title on f. 1r.
history.provenance: It was probably part of the Hautin library; it did not belong to Jean-Baptiste Hautin (who died in 1640), but was acquired by one of his descendants. After 1697, it entered into the collection of John Moore (1646-1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 . However, the manuscript is neither listed in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697) nor in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore's manuscripts, now CUL MS Oo.7.50.2, compiled by Thomas Tanner (1674-1735) after the publication of Bernard's catalogue.
history.acquisition:
Presented to the University Library in 1715 by
George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 . The royal bookplate engraved by John Pine in 1736 remains on pastedown.
